social_posts.post_text: Sad girl szn winter edition when it’s cold and you don’t want to leave your house or interact with anyone.

What’s your favorite Christmas tradition? We’re deaming of our wintry Christmas wonderland in the city filled with Christmas decorations, visits with Santa, milk and cookies, Charlee’s first time seeing snow, hot cocoa from Ralph’s, ice skating in Central Park, tea at the plaza, and strolling through holiday markets 🧸🎄🤶🏼🦌
Dairy of the intellectually curious girlies who are entering into their winter academia era 🏛️🕊️🤎
Tell me what’s missing on this list 🎄🦌🎁🤶🏼🧸 oh! Homemade cinnamon rolls on Christmas morning. That’s a must.
Can’t wait for more shenanigans with @leandracreativecophoto SOON 🫶🏼
We still love you @ralphscoffee even when you give Charlee regular instead of decaf 🐻🫶🏼

iPhone album crumbs 🍪 it’s been far too long since I’ve uploaded a static post, so here ya go- some of my favorite candids, memories, and moments tainted with the excitement of our new adventures coming very soon 🥹🧸🎄🫶🏼♥️🤶🏼
I’m having too much fun with photos now and I don’t want to let them go. Another photo album of core memories for the books 🚕🧸🫒🤎
And suddenly I feel alive and energized and whole and inspired and passionate with an insatiable appetite to create the fullest life I could ever imagine. It feels good to be finally home 🚕🧸🗽

First day back home in the city and there was an influx of holiday spirit and Christmas cheer in the air 🥰🧸🚕🎄🦌 rather than overdoing it and trying to cram everything in all at once, here’s how our day went: we avoided any area that could be potentially touched by Santacon, we had hot cocoa and chocolate chip cookies at @ralphscoffee , we walked around UES and admired all the stunning decked out brownstones, and then we went down to The Plaza Hotel to look at the Christmas decorations and had tea and got to visit Santa! Tonight, we’re going out for a mama daughter dinner followed by Christmas movies and popcorn before bed 🧸🤎🐻

Tis the season of giving, and for Charlee and me, gift giving is our love language. @chloecleroux inspired us to gift sweet treats to the people in the city we adore and appreciate, starting with the staff at @theplazahotel who have made some of our favorite New York City memories feel extra special 🚕🧸 I hope this inspires you to love a little more on the people who make the little moments hold the biggest space in your heart. (Okay, I’m starting to sound like a hallmark card so that’s my cue…) 👋🏻

A sight so beautiful I could cry. I hope this makes your Monday a little brighter. So many of you have been sending me the sweetest messages about how happy you are that Charlee and me are back in the city. There’s a dramatic energy shift when we’re here. Our spirits are lifted. We feel energized and passionate and hopeful again. There’s an insatiable desire to live a fuller and more purposeful life, especially during the little moments, the most important moments in between.
City sidewalks, busy sidewalks 🎄🧸🦌🚕 a glimpse of a very festive New York City with lots more to come!
Life lately in NYC feat. rainbow scarves, balaclavas, and plenty of love to keep us warm 🐻🧸
Winter academia Caitlyn unlocked 🐻 she’s euphoric and comes alive in New York City on cloudy rainy days that appear melancholic but give her the most joy on a visceral and existential level.

Charlee and I are so happy- happy in its most pure, euphoric form. There’s something about this city that makes us feel alive again. I feel undeservingly lucky at times and wonder how on earth I made it through these past several years knowing how good life could be today. It makes me incredibly emotional and I want to keep sharing this with you because I went from manically depressed and suicidal with debilitating panic attacks to the happiest I’ve ever felt in my life. I write this to urge you to keep going. Keep pushing forward and don’t give up. If you’re in a dark space and it feels like life is crashing down on you, I promise there’s a light just around the corner, even if you can’t see it. New York City Caitlyn is the fullest, best, most passionate and inspired version of herself. I love me when I’m here. I love the mother I become when I’m here. I love the creator I become when I’m here. I’m forever grateful for you, New York City, even when you break me in order to build me into an even better Caitlyn.

It’s Christmas time in New York City, you’re frolicking through the holiday markets, eating apple cider donuts and drinking spiced cider to keep warm and cosy.You watch the ice skaters glide around the rink arm in arm, there’s Christmas music playing in the background, and you realize that this moment right here with your best friend is the happiest you’ve felt in a very long time, maybe even ever.

It’s been a Christmas whirlwind of a week in New York City and we wouldn’t have it any other way! I hope these holiday themed upper east side townhomes give you the biggest boost of serotonin and help you fight off all the Sunday scaries. We love you! 🧸🎄🤶🏼

It’s the season for a Dark Academia Christmas:
-deep burgundy and forest green
-classical Christmas music 
-hand written Christmas cards 
-presents wrapped with brown paper and burgundy bows
-red wine and charcuterie boards filled with pomegranates, cheeses, drizzled honey, and crackers
-rereading and annotating Dickens A Christmas Carol
-gifting books to loved ones
-tying ribbons in your hair 
-red noses and roses cheeks from the cold 
-overcoats, large cashmere scarves and leather gloves 
-vanilla candles 
-elegant holiday soirées
Rainy days, croissants dipped in vanilla lattes, the smell of freshly baked bread, and daydreaming about Paris with your best friend. We love you @lappartement4f 🥖
Chasing Christmas themed facades all over the city makes me feel all kinds of cozy and merry and warm, even when it’s 30 degrees outside 🎄 4 more sleeps until Christmas!

Life lately: Christmas in New York City, lots of hot cocoa, plenty of core memories in the making, and dare I say some of the most joyous moments of my life. I love our old traditions, and I love making new ones with you just the same (maybe even more).

I just realized that I have a coffee cup in my hand in almost every photo I’m in and I’m not mad about it. Here’s to chaotic coffee drinking girlies who attempt a solid wellness routine but really, we’re just doing our best and that’s okay. Two more sleeps!

Ever since Charlee could speak she begged me to take her to the snow during Christmas time. Today, it snowed in New York City and I was able to capture her sweet expression- rosy cheeks, pink nose, bright eyed and elated as she watched the snow fall for the first time ever. ❄️

We’re exhausted 😅 but in the best way. We crammed two months worth of Christmas festivities into two weeks and (almost) checked off everything on our bucket list. It’s was an unforgettable Christmas and the amount of joy these past couple of weeks brought us was worth every minute of it (even when we had to wear three pairs of pants). I don’t know about you, but I’m ready for a fresh start and I’m ridiculously passionate and energized to dive back into my creative projects and endeavors. Can’t wait to share more with you!

The plaza hotel sounded better than a sublet, so Miss Claus worked her magic and made it happen. Happy Christmas, sweet Charlee. We didn’t get to do a lot of our classic holiday traditions this year, but we got to make new memories and start new traditions that will last us a lifetime and a half. I love living this New York City life with you, especially when we celebrate tiny (and extravagant) moments.

What a whirlwind of a weekend! Miss Claus is exhausted, but her heart is filled to the brim with joy. The recipe for the perfect day after Christmas is a slow morning (with French toast, croissants, and coffee), followed by some upper east side shopping adventures with Charlee. We’ll end the day watch classic Disney films snuggled up on the couch with popcorn and cocoa before bed.

Spent most of the morning in bed reading and writing. Got dressed up to take Charlee to the New York public library where we sat for hours doing more reading and writing because that’s our ultimate way to destress and unwind. We’re going to end the day at the bookstore, make a nice dinner (probably pasta with garlic bread) and watch classic Disney films (perhaps Winnie the Pooh or Peter Pan). I hope you found peace in your day like we did. It’s a weird week. Weird but wonderful.

Not sure what dimension we’re in, but instead of panicking and falling into a deep depression like I do every year, this time I’m riding it out and feeling my feelings and sleeping and giving myself permission to throw my worries off of our 19th floor balcony. Happy Monday! Or whatever day it is?

I took care of myself and it wasn’t pretty. 
I’ve disappointed people by prioritizing my time and energy. I’ve had to let go of relationships with friends and family that were toxic. I ugly cried in therapy, forced myself to shower when I didn’t want to, paid overdue bills, and didn’t over exercise, even though my mind told me that I needed to. I’ve taken accountability for all the times I’ve messed up and hurt people along the way. I’ve come to terms with the fact that taking care of myself is an evolving process of fighting, and sometimes crawling, my way through the growing pains of life. It’s messy and imperfect, just like me, and that’s what makes it beautiful.

This has been one of the most emotional years of my life filled with the highest of high moments and the lowest of lows. It’s been a whirlwind with lots of change, and I’m grateful that we’ll finally be approaching stable ground in the new year. I’ve written a lot about the concept of “home”, whether it be a person, place, or thing. This year a taught me that home is truly an amalgamation of all three- a trifecta that works synchronously with one another. Home feels like comfort, but it also makes you feel alive and energized and excited to wake up in the morning. Wherever you are and whatever you plan on doing over 2023, I hope you find your version of home. All of the lessons and road blocks we’ve faced over this past year have made it very clear that we’ve finally found it here in New York City.

2023 for me means: throwing ridiculous wellness regimens and routines out the window, indulging more in the things I truly love like Diet Coke and dark chocolate and cheese. It’s the year of being unapologetically chaotic and not giving a fuck about pleasing everybody else around me. I’m going to start drinking wine and eating cake for breakfast and not spend ridiculous amounts of money of skincare that doesn’t work for shit just because an influencer recommended it, and instead, invest that money into financial goals and traveling with Charlee. I’m going to start creating in different mediums and cross pollinate between different social platforms and create content I love rather than trying to appease what I think the algorithm wants. Maybe I’ll date, I’ll definitely fall on my ass, and I’ll probably quit the corporate world or maybe I won’t. I’ll have goals and dreams and I’ll pursue them with all of me rather than spreading myself too thin and saying yes to everything. I’ll learn how to set boundaries. I must promise myself to write everyday and when I fail to uphold my promise, I’m not going to beat myself up about it, and I’ll try again tomorrow. I need to start therapy again, only so I can give myself a safe space to unpack my baggage and air my dirty laundry. I’ll have days when I’ll look in the mirror and detest my body and myself and I’ll try to convince myself that I don’t deserve good things and I’ll give myself permission to feel my feelings. And the next morning when I wake up, pillow damp and blurry eyed, I’ll remind myself that I’m a girl queen pu$$y boss b!tch and I get to try again.

Starting the new year with this: simple and significant, zero expectations, living presently and giving myself the space to dream a little bigger and life more spontaneously. More dancing and laughter and late night trips to get pizza and time to read and write and explore and learn and create and say yes to the things that make me excited to get out of bed in the morning.

I was a ballet dancer for 17 years. I remember when I was about 12 years old, we did an Alice in Wonderland themed ballet recital. If you’re not familiar with the story, there’s a scene where Alice walks through a garden and meets a bunch of different flowers who sing and talk to her. My ballet teacher wanted to emulate that scene for one of the routines in our show. During one of our first rehearsals, our teacher lined all of us dancers in one row to let us know which flower we would be. I so desperately wanted to be the deep red rose, but would have been happy with the purple Iris, too. When it came to be my turn to learn which flower I would play she stopped to analyze me. Her eyes glazed over as she looked me up and down and after a long pause she finally said in front of everyone, “it’s too bad you won’t be able to fit in any of the prettier flower costumes. I guess you’ll have to be a Mum. It’s a mumu so it shouldn’t be a problem.” The chrysanthemum costume was in fact one of the most hideous and unflattering costumes I had ever seen. She draped it over me and put me in the back corner and I bit my cheek hard until I tasted blood to prevent myself from shedding tears in front of the other dancers. So alas, here I stand almost 20 years later looking at this portrait of beautiful billowing chrysanthemums, and I’m finally realizing that being a mum wasn’t so bad after all.
Rainy days in the west village. Coffee. Waffles. Croissant aux amandes. Books. Journals. Good conversations. People watching. & you.
All she wanted was some breakfast- bread and butter, perhaps jam.

Hey guess what? Charlee and I are launching a Podcast this month! Hello again. Also, I’m exhausted and it’s been a very rough week of sickness and travel and hotel hopping. We’re taking a quick pit stop to California to visit family and tie up some loose ends before coming back to nyc. Let me tell you, as someone who vowed to romanticize my life as much as possible, living and traveling bicoastal as a single mother working as a full time corporate slave is not very romantic and absolutely exhausting. Mental health is going to be a huge priority for me over the next several weeks before we return to the city. But nevertheless, this podcast project with Charlee has been one of the most enjoyable creative outlets I’ve ever indulged in. It fills my cup and reminds me why I love being here with you, sharing our stories and all of our adventures together. As I’ve grown to love this new season of life, I’ve been more confident and unapologetic in creating things I love without worrying about others’ opinions (the algorithm included). And I just wanted to say I love you for supporting me and for sharing the same affinity I have for aesthetics. Much more of that to come. And much much more to come about our podcast SOON.
Target audience: lovers of baguettes, croissants, chocolate filled treats, Chanel, books, flowers wrapped in newspapers, vintage lockets with love notes inside. You know- little things.

Sometimes I’ll listen to songs that transport me back to a time when I was dreaming of living in New York City and “making it”. When I’m running around and absorbing the city around me, I realize that I’m living out what I’ve always truly wanted and it’s surreal- like I’m floating and I’m not afraid anymore.
Late night trips to the library on rainy days with you. Reading, writing, studying, maybe sneaking in a coffee or two, and learning how to use our inside voices.

social_posts.post_text: There are no rules, limits, or bounds in exploring all of your curiosities. Make art, learn calculus and foreign languages, play an instrument, take a ballet class, paint with watercolors, take photos of everything, conduct science experiments and explore the anatomy and physiology of our incredible bodies. Don’t let anyone tell you that you can be a scientist and an artist and a mathematician and a historian and a writer and lover of literature. You can do it all, you can pick and choose, you can obsess over 1-2 subjects or devour them all. Find the things you love and explore them deeper with an insatiable appetite to be a life long learner.

The mondayest Tuesday to ever exist feat. a love letter to @barpisellino - one of our favorite coffee shops in the city. Tell me what you’re drinking this morning- coffee or tea? With milk or without?

Nothing fancy. Nothing groundbreaking. Just two best friends who perpetually wear all black, running around New York City searching for new places to explore, making core memories, and making playlists that comprise the soundtrack of our lives. 🎶

Craving comfort? Me, too. Here are some ways to find comfort when life feels unstable:

•Rest. Sleep is the most important thing you can do to help mitigate any sort or stress or discomfort in your life. Prioritize quality rest. 
•Wellness Routine. Whatever that means to you. 
•Listen. Podcasts and audiobooks are my favorite way to escape my mind. I like to habit stack, so I’ll take a walk or clean up the house and listen to a book or podcast episode. It’s one of my favorite ways to decompress. 
•Scent. Pick out a candle that reminds you of home or a good memory and light it when you start to feel uneasy. 
•Write. Journaling, annotating in a good book, writing lists, blogging, and everything in between. Get it all out on paper to get you out of your head. 
•Move. Take a walk outside, yoga, pilates, or any type of movement that makes your body feel good and grounded. 
•Nourish. I’m all about treating yourself. But if you’re looking for calm and comfort, it’s time to start investing in your health by feeding your body healthy, whole, balanced, unprocessed foods. There are so many tasty recipes (both sweet and savory) to satisfy any craving without giving you that ick feeling if you’re eating something heavy and processed. 
•Talk. I’m a huge advocate of therapy and I truly believe that every single human on this planet can benefit from it. 
•Gather. Have coffee or dinner with a friend. Surround yourself with people who love and support you. 
•Create. Carve out time to do something creative. Work toward your creative or entrepreneurial goals. Try something new. Step outside of your comfort zone and indulge in exploration.

And by you, I mean the croissant that has my name written all over it. Happy Friday, sweet friends. Please enjoy a bread rich breakfast with me- preferably croissants of any kind or a baguette with butter, perhaps jam? I love you all.

To my dear sweet Charlee, thank you for being the most radiant light of my life. Thank you for being my best friend, my daughter, my partner in crime, and everything in between. Being your mama is truly the greatest gift I could ever ask for and I simply don’t have the words to thank you for helping me grow into the woman and mother I’ve become today. It’s January 28 and today you’re 12- still my little girl who’s not so little but still not old enough to be a big girl- The awkward in between when life starts to feel a little strange and unusual and difficult to navigate. But as life continues to get more challenging, I hope you know I’ll always be here to guide you, and more importantly, listen. You and I share our hearts with one another and I hope that never goes away. You will always be the most important person in my life. You’re my world. And I love you more than words could fathom. Happy birthday, sweet Charlee. Welcome to year 12. I can’t wait to celebrate the beautiful person you’ve become with lots of cake, magic, birthday playlists, and planning our next big adventure together.

Happy Sunday, kids!
Lots of exciting news for me to share with you this week! Stay tuned and until then…
Rest, drink water (and wine. and coffee. perhaps tea.)
Read something (I’m reading Flux by @orioncarloto and Selected Poems by John Keats)
Cook something (even if it’s heating up Dino chicken nuggies or baking pillsbury cookies)
Eat dessert (I’m eating cake)
Write, journal, create 
Watch your favorite comfort film (mine is winnie the pooh or the princess diaries or devil wears prada or breakfast at tiffany’s)

I love you all so much

I see your crippling anxiety and I raise you one existential meltdown. 

Writing to commiserate with those of you who are feeling the weight of the world today. I’m in a strange period of waiting, and patience is not my strong suit. There are an abundance of positive changes happening in mine and Charlee’s life right now, but as we wait to embark on new adventures, I can’t help but wonder if I’m making the right decision for myself and as a mother. I always have to remind myself that not making a decision is making a decision and it’s usually the wrong one. So I’ve confidently made my decisions. Fingers crossed?

@inagarten ate here a few days ago and I would have given my left ovary to meet her and say hello and ask her if store bought cookies were okay to bring to my daughters class instead of homemade cookies because I’m tired. 

We love you @buvettenyc thanks for the memories and good eats as always.

We’ve been getting rather deep with these existential questions lately. You might not have the mental capacity to ask yourself this question right now, but promise me you’ll tuck it away in your brain and savor it for later?

Self care is really fucking hard if you’ve ever struggled with body image or mental health issues. I’m a masochist and I’m still trying to figure out what self care means to me. I don’t want to take a bath or go get a massage or get acupuncture. When I truly truly feel down in the dumps I don’t want to do anything. Sometimes I want to sit in the pain I feel. Yesterday, I was sick with a fever, aches, chills and rather than chilling tf out and resting like I should have been doing, I sat there, beating myself up because I didn’t get a work out in because I physically could not move no matter how hard I tried. Mental health sucks. Self care is an enigma and I’m convinced no one has it figured out. Maybe I sound dumb, but also maybe I’m not the only who struggles like this?
Saturday mornings feat. a few of my favorite things. Tell me some of your favorites below!

Sundays are for lovers and bagels with your best friend. Bagels with cream cheese, jelly donuts, hot black coffee, a walk to the bookstore, back home to unwind, change your sheets, clean the house, rest, cook a homemade meal, prep for the week, read, and bed before 10pm. Oh, and dark chocolate dipped strawberries for dessert.
Mondays: fries, cheese, bread, wine, and olives for lunch. Add in a book for good measure, some solitude, a power nap, and a mid-day slice of cake.
I love you, New York. Thanks for always making us feel at home, even when we didn’t have one <3

A place of peace and quiet amidst a bustling city. @argosybookstore is one of my favorite comfort spots in New York. I imagine most New Yorkers have their own list of places like this- a place to escape, breathe, and recenter yourself when life feels extra heavy and noisy.
All black, buried in a balaclava with an attitude that’s palpable from another planet. And the 👼🏼🐑🤍🦢🕊️ side of you competes with the 🖤🏴‍☠️🐈‍⬛♟️👹 part of you until the coffee kicks in.

“Godhood is just like girlhood: a begging to be believed.” 
Can you imagine being a tween or teen girl in 2023? The inundation of social media and always having to be “on” and feeling exposed 24/7 while also feeling overwhelmingly alone and misunderstood.

It’s a Saturday morning in New York City. The breakfast options are of abundance so which do you choose? Are we going to get pancakes at a cozy diner? Are we going to a French bakery to eat our weight in pastries? Are we being good and eating a bowl of warm oatmeal with cream, raisins, walnuts and brown sugar? Are we being naughty and eating dark chocolate sea salt cookies? Are we choosing something comforting like freshly baked banana bread with a dot of butter? Either way there’s coffee to be shared, conversations to be had, and an appreciation for the start of a slow restful weekend ahead of us.

Despite my cynicism, Valentine’s Day is one of my favorite holidays. I’ve been lucky enough to have Charlee as my Valentines for the last 12 years and I wouldn’t have it any other way! We’re still planning out our dinner menu and we’re torn between heart shaped ravioli vs heart shaped pizza. There will be chocolate for dessert and cake for breakfast because we deserve it. 

If you don’t have a Valentine this year, you can be ours! There’s always room at the table for you <3

Here’s to romanticizing the little moments in between -

I can’t wait to nest in our new home and enjoy the little moments like making coffee in the morning and spreading butter on an English muffin that just came out of the toaster and eating pizza on the floor of our apartment on the first night we move in with lit candles and jazz music and conversations about all the exciting things we’re going to do tomorrow and inviting Charlee’s new friends over to decorate sugar cookies and changing our bedding on a Sunday morning with new candles to christen and fill our home with scent of promise and stability and a new place to make memories with you.

This Valentine’s Day, Charlee and I are finally back home in New York City. We took a 5am flight and have been up for about 48 hours straight. We’re exhausted. But it’s the good kind of exhaustion. We’ve had to do this bicoastal back and fourth situation between NY and CA for about a year - that’s 6+ plane rides back and fourth, and for someone who’s biggest fear is flying, the emotional havoc this caused my mental health can not be fathomed into words. The anxiety was unbearable. This Valentine’s Day, not only do I get to spend the the holiday in our favorite city in the world with my favorite person in the world… I finally get to find calm, stability, and comfort knowing that we’re moving into our brand new nyc apartment with no intentions of going anywhere anytime soon. Today we’re celebrating love in every capacity- love for one another, love for a new chapter in the city we love most, love for our home, love for romanticizing every moment in our lives, and love for you. Oh, and love for dessert because tonight we’re celebrating with chocolate covered strawberries, princess cake from Sant Ambroeus, pink & white cookies from William Greenberg, and lots of pasta and bread.

Coffee dates, upper east side walks, nyc dogs, taxis, people watching, apartment shopping, nesting, late night dinners, blurry grainy film, new candles, more dessert, romanticizing life, overwhelming gratitude, living in a city that finally feels like home <3

Dear beloved and belated Valentine’s Day, I must recap the magical week we’ve had being back in the city as we move into our new home. Gratitude is an understatement. I’m overwhelmed with the abundance of love flooding into and out of my heart. And not just because we’re finally back in nyc, but also because my podcast is launching SOON as well as a brand spanking new website, blog, and a sneak peak into a passion project I’ve been working on for a very long time!! I’ll be sharing more tomorrow so stay tuned!! <3

Welcome to the first sneak peak of the Big Sis Podcast! I’m Caitlyn and I’m a writer living in New York City with my 11 year old daughter, Charlee. Without giving too much away, I’m adhd, multi passionate, and a little bit chaotic. I’m a Virgo sun, Aquarius rising, Taurus moon. I’m an INTJ on the meyers brigg scale. I don’t have my shit together but I can tell you that I romanticize every moment of my life, I devour books, jazzy dinner parties, Ella Fitzgerald, coffee, and a home cooked meal. I love women who love too much and eat chocolate for breakfast and unapologetically dine solo with wine and a book in hand. I can tell you that I’ve been through a lot, just like you, and I wanted a space to share my stories and experiences so you and I can come together to commiserate and maybe learn a thing or two. I hope you come back each week and listen to new episodes as Charlee and I share stories, experiences, and adventures in New York City.

“But who wants and easy life? It’s boring!” As I’ve grown, I’ve learned to live at a pace that feels good for me- a healthy balance of grit and determination while romanticizing the little things in life- especially eating dessert for breakfast. Perfect balance? Certainly not. But I get better at it every day.

When I was a little girl, my grandpa used to take me to this cafe in the hometown where I grew up. Sure, we could get sandwiches or salads or anything that was lunch related, but my grandpa wanted to get pie with homemade whip cream. His favorite was always strawberry rhubarb and he and I would share a slice together and dollop extra spoonfuls of whip on top. During the warmer months, the café would have homemade vanilla bean ice cream, which was his ultimate favorite. We would sit and talk about school and the different fruits and vegetables that he was growing in his garden. He would talk about the fruit that grew abundantly in his avocado and orange grove and how my grandmother just needed a tuberose plant because they were her favorite flower. And because I’ve been missing my grandparents a lot lately, I wanted to get this pie in their honor.

Tell me if you’re celebrating today and if so, what is your favorite pie? Do you prefer whipped cream on top or a la mode?

Growing up, I was never excited about spring or summer- probably because I lived somewhere without seasons. (365 days of 75 degree weather). This might sound appealing to the majority, but for Charlee and me, we crave change. We crave the changing of the seasons. We live our lives according to the seasons. We bake and cook seasonally. We celebrate seasonally. And living in nyc has finally given us the gift of seasons. Spring time in New York city. Sounds lovely, doesn’t it? I’m most excited to create new traditions and memories with my favorite person in the whole world. What are you most excited for?

Springtime in New York City. concept: resurgence of spring blooms in central park, tea at the plaza hotel with your best friend, outdoor picnics with cake and champagne, gleaming chandeliers, frank sinatra and Ella Fitzgerald playing in the background, drying flowers, baking strawberry honey muffins, reading spring inspired literature, laying down in the grass having deep conversations with a friend or a lover new beginnings, sweet dreams, soft tousled hair wild and undone, classical music

Creating our sanctuary one book at a time. Baking through family recipes in our new kitchen. Watching old films. Burning new candles with new scents for new memories. Writing and reading in cosy nooks of our home. Romanticizing coffee in the morning, wine at night, and cake for breakfast. Spraying the linens of our beds with light rose and delicate florals. Hosting intimate dinner parties with jazz on the record player. Late night conversations. Pancakes on the weekends. Slow mornings. Antiques for decoration. Observing the city out of our window late at night and feeling small, but significant.

the juxtaposition of my emotions over the past couple of weeks have my head spinning. Moments like these make it all better- spring time, walks through Central Park, after school ice cream dates, watching the flowers start to bloom, new candles, iced coffee, and you.

I dreamt of @stanleytucci making me baked pasta for breakfast and reading to me. When I woke up and realized he wasn’t there, I decided to make some myself and listen to his audiobook instead. 

I didn’t have pancetta so I improvised and made it with artichoke, extra Parmesan, sun dried tomatoes, and of course, peas. 

Preheat your oven to 350
Cook your farfalle pasta Al dente
Stir in your bechamel (or other cream sauce) (don’t drown your noodles- just let the sauce kiss your pasta and let the other ingredients shine)
Add in your sun dried tomatoes, artichoke hearts, tons of Parmesan, garlic, cooked onions, butter, salt, pepper 
Bake for 20-25 mins (I like the top layer of noods extra crispy)

I want a home mostly just to welcome people into it. There will be bowls of candy for guests themed around whatever holiday comes next. The cookie jar is full. The home will always have candles burning that are subtle, warm, and welcoming like freshly baked banana bread. I’ll always say “I was just about to make a coffee/tea/ cocoa, would you like one?” There will always be a book within arms reach- whatever catches their eye. Once they start saying they really should be going, l’ll remind them that there’s an empty bed if they wish to stay, and I’m making cinnamon rolls tomorrow in the morning. There’s champagne and sparkling juice hidden on a high shelf just in case somebody announces something to be celebrated while they’re here. There is an extra chair in the living room, at the table, and it’s for you. I want to be able to say “if you’re ever in trouble, come to me.”
